To draw a chessboard using LaTeX, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's an example of how to create a LaTeX document that draws a chessboard based on a given FEN (FENdered Position Notation) string.

First, make sure to include the following packages in your preamble:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{xcolor}
\usepackage{pgffor}

% Define colors for the pieces
\definecolor{wk}{RGB}{255,255,255}
\definecolor{wq}{RGB}{255,255,255}
\definecolor{wb}{RGB}{235,235,235}
\definecolor{wr}{RGB}{139,69,19}
\definecolor{wbk}{RGB}{128,128,128}
\definecolor{wrk}{RGB}{66,47,8}

% Define the chessboard style with colors
\newchessgame[color=wb,boardcolor=wbk]
\setchessboard{size=3.5cm}

% Define the FEN string and initialize the board
\newcommand{\fen}[1]{\gdef\FEN{#1}\global\let\TempBoard\empty\relax
  \foreach \square in {1,2,...,64}{%
    \edef\temp{\getchessboardcsname{\the\numexpr\FENnumofpiece{1,\square}\relax}}%
    \edef\temp{\ifx\temp\empty \edef\TempBoard{\TempBoard X}%
               \else \edef\TempBoard{\TempBoard \temp}%
               \fi}%
  }%
  \global\let\board=\TempBoard
}
```

Now, you can use the `\fen` command to set the FEN string and draw the board. Here's an example usage:

```latex
\begin{document}

% Set the FEN string
\fen{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

% Draw the board
\chessboard[position=\xchessresult{startpos}=\board]

\end{document}
```

This example sets the FEN string `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1` and draws the corresponding chessboard. Make sure to compile this code with a LaTeX compiler that supports the `chessboard` package, such as `pdflatex`.

